nderstanding of the respiratory system to be able to prevent and manage respiratory related problems? Join Donn Kropp as he takes you on an exciting journey through this system. This course sets the ground work for you to understand various respiratory diseases and conditions. ','inherit','closed','closed','','168-revision-5','','','2011-08-23 04:45:29','2011-08-23 04:45:29','',168,'http://clickplayceu.com/2011/08/168-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(221,1,'2011-08-24 06:09:43','2011-08-24 06:09:43','','Respiratory System Part 1: The Foundation','','inherit','closed','closed','','respiratory1','','','2011-08-24 06:09:43','2011-08-24 06:09:43','',168,'http://clickplayceu.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Respiratory1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(182,1,'2011-08-23 04:45:45','2011-08-23 04:45:45','Have you heard of MRSA? If you havenâ€™t you should. Your life or someone elseâ€™s may depend on it. M.R.S.A stands for Methicillin Resistant Staphylococcus Aureus, commonly referred to as â€œMERSAâ€ or just â€œStaph Infectionâ€. This course will help youÂ  understand MRSA so that you can institute safe and effective practices that will benefit yourself and the individuals you serve.\r\n\r\nMRSA has had a relatively short existence. It was first noticed in nursing homes and hospitals in the early 1960â€˜s. Until the mid-20th century, infectious diseases were the leading cause of death.Thanks to our good friend Alexander Flemingâ€™s accidental discovery of penicillin in 1928, there was a huge decrease in the incidences of diseases caused by bacteria.Â  Flemingâ€™s discovery took a little while to gain traction but when it did in the early 1940â€™s, this started the era of the â€œAntibiotic Phenomenonâ€. Antibiotics were hailed as miracle drugs. Previously untreatable conditions could now be overcome with a simple pill.Â  Unfortunately this isnâ€™t a happily-ever-after story.\r\n\r\nJust a decade later a resistant strain of Staphylococcus Aureus emerged. It was resistant not only to penicillin, but to newer antibiotics that were being developed such as: erythromycin, streptomycin, and tetracycline. A very costly lesson was being learned at this point; that lesson was, â€œBacteria have the ability to mutate.â€ Learn more about this superbug as seasoned registered nurse, Donn Kropp, demystifies this scourge.\r\n\r\n<strong>Course Objectives</strong>\r\nUpon completion of this course you will be able to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Understand bacteria and their significance</li>\r\n	<li>Differentiate between Staphylococcus Aureus and MRSA</li>\r\n	<li>Understand the origins of MRSA and its ramifications on health</li>\r\n	<li>Gain knowledge about colonization vs infection</li>\r\n	<li>Be enlightened about the mechanisms of bacterial mutation and resistance</li>\r\n	<li>Learn how to identify, manage and prevent MRSA infections</li>\r\n	<li>Understand treatment options</li>\r\n	<li>Know the importance of instituting safe and effective infection control practices</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Chapter Content</strong>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Objectives</li>\r\n	<li>Introduction</li>\r\n	<li>Understanding Bacteria</li>\r\n	<li>Staph. vs MRSA</li>\r\n	<li>Origins of MRSA</li>\r\n	<li>Colonization vs Infection</li>\r\n	<li>Mutation and Resistance</li>\r\n	<li>Identify, Manage, Prevent</li>\r\n	<li>Treatment Options</li>\r\n	<li>Conclusion</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Course Approvals</strong>: This course is pending approval by the following boards\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>NAB: This educational offering has been reviewed by the National Continuing Education Review Service (NCERS) of the National Association of Boards of Examiners of Long Term Care Administrators (NAB).</li>\r\n	<li>California Adult Residential Facility (ARF) Vendor No. 2000149-735-2 Course Approval No. ____________</li>\r\n	<li>Residential Care Facility for the Elderly (RCFE) Vendor No. 2000149-740-2 Course Approval No._________</li>\r\n	<li>Group Home (GH) Vendor No. 2000149-730-2Â  Course Approval No. _______